name: Get-ProcessMitigation
synopsis: Gets the current process mitigation settings, either from the registry, from a running process, or saves all to a XML.
description: Gets all process mitigation settings either by process name (either running or from -Registry), or by process ID. Can also save all settings to an XML file.

parameters.name: FullPolicy
parameters.description: Returns every processes' current mitigation settings in the registry

parameters.name: Id
parameters.description: Process Id to retrieve current running process mitigation settings from

parameters.name: Name
parameters.description: Current process name to get current running (Or from registry) process mitigation settings from one (Can be more than one instance)

parameters.name: RegistryConfigFilePath
parameters.description: File to save the current registry process mitigation configuration to

parameters.name: RunningProcesses
parameters.description: Pull the current process mitigation settings from a running instance instead of the registry.

parameters.name: System
parameters.description: Pulls the current system defaults for process mitigations.

name: Get-PSReadLineKeyHandler
synopsis: Gets the key bindings for the PSReadLine module.
description: Gets the key bindings for the PSReadLine module.

parameters.name: Bound
parameters.description: Include functions that are bound.

parameters.name: Unbound
parameters.description: Include functions that are unbound.

name: Get-PSReadLineOption
synopsis: Returns the values for the options that can be configured.
description: Get-PSReadLineOption returns the current state of the settings that can be configured by Set-PSReadLineOption.

name: Get-ScriptAnalyzerRule
synopsis: Gets the script analyzer rules on the local computer.
description: Gets the script analyzer rules on the local computer. You can select rules by Name, Severity, Source, or SourceType, or even particular words in the rule description.

parameters.name: CustomRulePath
parameters.description: Gets the Script Analyzer rules in the specified path in addition to the standard Script Analyzer rules. By default, PSScriptAnalyzer gets only the standard rules specified in the Microsoft.Windows.PowerShell.ScriptAnalyzer.BuiltinRules.dll file in the module.

parameters.name: RecurseCustomRulePath
parameters.description: Searches the CustomRulePath location recursively to add rules defined in files in subdirectories of the path. By default, Get-ScriptAnalyzerRule adds only the custom rules in the specified path.

parameters.name: Name
parameters.description: Gets only rules with the specified names or name patterns. Wildcards are supported. If you list multiple names or patterns, it gets rules that match any of the name patterns, as though the name patterns were joined by an OR.

parameters.name: Severity
parameters.description: Gets only rules with the specified severity values. Valid values are Information, Warning, and Error. By default, Get-ScriptAnalyzerRule gets all rules.

name: Invoke-Formatter
synopsis: Formats a script text based on the input settings or default settings.
description: The Invoke-Formatter cmdlet takes a string parameter named ScriptDefinition and formats it according to the input settings parameter Settings. If no Settings parameter is provided, the cmdlet assumes the default code formatting settings as defined in Settings/CodeFormatting.psd1.

parameters.name: ScriptDefinition
parameters.description: The script text to be formated. NOTE : Unlike ScriptBlock parameter, the ScriptDefinition parameter require a string value.

parameters.name: Settings
parameters.description: A settings hashtable or a path to a PowerShell data file (.psd1) file that contains the settings.

parameters.name: Range
parameters.description: The range within which formatting should take place. The parameter is an array of integers of length 4 such that the first, second, third and last elements correspond to the start line number, start column number, end line number and end column number. These numbers must be greater than 0.

name: Invoke-ScriptAnalyzer
synopsis: Evaluates a script or module based on selected best practice rules
description: Invoke-ScriptAnalyzer evaluates a script or module files (.ps1, .psm1 and .psd1 files) based on a collection of best practice rules and returns objects that represent rule violations. It also includes special rules to analyze DSC resources.

parameters.name: Path
parameters.description: Specifies the path to the scripts or module to be analyzed. Wildcard characters are supported.

parameters.name: CustomRulePath
parameters.description: Uses only the custom rules defined in the specified paths to the analysis. To still use the built-in rules, add the -IncludeDefaultRules switch.

parameters.name: RecurseCustomRulePath
parameters.description: Adds rules defined in subdirectories of the CustomRulePath location. By default, Invoke-ScriptAnalyzer uses only the custom rules defined in the specified file or directory. To still use the built-in rules, additionally use the -IncludeDefaultRules switch.

parameters.name: ExcludeRule
parameters.description: Omits the specified rules from the Script Analyzer test. Wildcard characters are supported.

parameters.name: IncludeDefaultRules
parameters.description: Invoke default rules along with Custom rules

parameters.name: IncludeRule
parameters.description: Runs only the specified rules in the Script Analyzer test. By default, PSScriptAnalyzer runs all rules.

parameters.name: Severity
parameters.description: After running Script Analyzer with all rules, this parameter selects rule violations with the specified severity.

parameters.name: Recurse
parameters.description: Runs Script Analyzer on the files in the Path directory and all subdirectories recursively.

parameters.name: SuppressedOnly
parameters.description: Returns rules that are suppressed, instead of analyzing the files in the path.

parameters.name: Fix
parameters.description: Fixes certain warnings which contain a fix in their DiagnosticRecord.

parameters.name: EnableExit
parameters.description: Exits PowerShell and returns an exit code equal to the number of error records. This can be useful in CI systems.

parameters.name: ReportSummary
parameters.description: Writes a report summary of the found warnings to the host.

parameters.name: Settings
parameters.description: File path that contains user profile or hash table for ScriptAnalyzer

parameters.name: ScriptDefinition
parameters.description: Runs Invoke-ScriptAnalyzer on commands, functions, or expressions in a string. You can use this feature to analyze statements, expressions, and functions, independent of their script context.

parameters.name: SaveDscDependency
parameters.description: Resolve DSC resource dependency

name: Set-ProcessMitigation
synopsis: Commands to enable and disable process mitigations or set them in bulk from an XML file.
description: Used to turn on and off various process mitigation settings. Can also apply (Or Validate) an XML file to apply settings for many processes at once.

parameters.name: Disable
parameters.description: Comma separated list of mitigations to disable. Disable list takes priority over enable list. If specified in both, it will be disabled.

parameters.name: EAFModules
parameters.description: Modules to be added to the EAF+ mitigation.

parameters.name: Enable
parameters.description: Comma separated list of mitigations to enable. Disable list takes priority over enable list. If specified in both, it will be disabled.

parameters.name: Force
parameters.description: Overrides a system setting either on or off depending on the level this is set at. Will force "on"/"off" all mitigations provided in the -Enable list

parameters.name: IsValid
parameters.description: Set to check the given XML file for validity. Requires local .xsd

parameters.name: Name
parameters.description: Name of the process to apply mitigation settings to. Can be in the format "notepad" or "notepad.exe"

parameters.name: PolicyFilePath
parameters.description: An XML file with mitigation settings for many processes that is applied to the registry

parameters.name: Remove
parameters.description: Removes a mitigation entry from the registry.

parameters.name: Reset
parameters.description: Resets a specific mitigation entry to defer.

parameters.name: System
parameters.description: Used to configure system defaults rather than individual apps.

name: Set-PSReadLineKeyHandler
synopsis: Binds or rebinds keys to user defined or PSReadLine provided key handlers.
description: This cmdlet is used to customize what happens when a particular key or sequence of keys is pressed while PSReadLine is reading input.

parameters.name: Chord
parameters.description: The key or sequence of keys to be bound to a Function or ScriptBlock. A single binding is specified with a single string. If the binding is a sequence of keys, the keys are separated with a comma, e.g. "Ctrl+X,Ctrl+X". Note that this parameter accepts multiple strings. Each string is a separate binding, not a sequence of keys for a single binding.

parameters.name: ScriptBlock
parameters.description: The ScriptBlock is called when the Chord is entered. The ScriptBlock is passed one or sometimes two arguments. The first argument is the key pressed (a ConsoleKeyInfo.)  The second argument could be any object depending on the context.

parameters.name: BriefDescription
parameters.description: A brief description of the key binding. Used in the output of cmdlet Get-PSReadLineKeyHandler.

parameters.name: Description
parameters.description: A more verbose description of the key binding. Used in the output of the cmdlet Get-PSReadLineKeyHandler.

parameters.name: Function
parameters.description: The name of an existing key handler provided by PSReadLine. This parameter allows one to rebind existing key bindings or to bind a handler provided by PSReadLine that is currently unbound.

parameters.name: ViMode
parameters.description: Specify which vi mode the binding applies to.

name: Set-PSReadLineOption
synopsis: Customizes the behavior of command line editing in PSReadLine.
description: The Set-PSReadLineOption cmdlet is used to customize the behavior of the PSReadLine module when editing the command line.

parameters.name: EditMode
parameters.description: Specifies the command line editing mode. This will reset any key bindings set by Set-PSReadLineKeyHandler.

parameters.name: PromptText
parameters.description: When there is a parse error, PSReadLine changes a part of the prompt red. PSReadLine analyzes your prompt function to determine how it can change just the color of part of your prompt, but this analysis cannot be 100% reliable.

parameters.name: ContinuationPrompt
parameters.description: Specifies the string displayed at the beginning of the second and subsequent lines when multi-line input is being entered. Defaults to '>> '. The empty string is valid.

parameters.name: HistoryNoDuplicates
parameters.description: Repeated commands will usually be added to history to preserve ordering during recall, but typically you don't want to see the same command multiple times when recalling or searching the history.

parameters.name: AddToHistoryHandler
parameters.description: Specifies a ScriptBlock that can be used to control which commands get added to PSReadLine history.

parameters.name: CommandValidationHandler
parameters.description: Specifies a ScriptBlock that is called from ValidateAndAcceptLine. If an exception is thrown, validation fails and the error is reported.

parameters.name: HistorySearchCursorMovesToEnd
parameters.description: When using `HistorySearchBackward` and `HistorySearchForward`, the default behavior leaves the cursor at the end of the search string if any.

parameters.name: MaximumHistoryCount
parameters.description: Specifies the maximum number of commands to save in PSReadLine history.

parameters.name: MaximumKillRingCount
parameters.description: Specifies the maximum number of items stored in the kill ring.

parameters.name: ShowToolTips
parameters.description: When displaying possible completions, show tooltips in the list of completions.

parameters.name: ExtraPromptLineCount
parameters.description: Use this option if your prompt spans more than one line.

parameters.name: Colors
parameters.description: The Colors parameter is used to specify various colors used by PSReadLine.

parameters.name: DingTone
parameters.description: When BellStyle is set to Audible, specifies the tone of the beep.

parameters.name: DingDuration
parameters.description: When BellStyle is set to Audible, specifies the duration of the beep.

parameters.name: BellStyle
parameters.description: Specifies how PSReadLine should respond to various error and ambiguous conditions.

parameters.name: CompletionQueryItems
parameters.description: Specifies the maximum number of completion items that will be shown without prompting.

parameters.name: WordDelimiters
parameters.description: Specifies the characters that delimit words for functions like ForwardWord or KillWord.

parameters.name: HistorySearchCaseSensitive
parameters.description: Specifies the searching history is case sensitive in functions like ReverseSearchHistory or HistorySearchBackward.

parameters.name: HistorySaveStyle
parameters.description: Specifies how PSReadLine should save history.

parameters.name: HistorySavePath
parameters.description: Specifies the path to the file where history is saved.

parameters.name: AnsiEscapeTimeout
parameters.description: This option is specific to Windows when input is redirected, e.g. when running under `tmux` or `screen`.

parameters.name: ViModeIndicator
parameters.description: This option sets the visual indication for the current mode in Vi mode - either insert mode or command mode.
